<h1>Central concepts</h1>

<h2>API</h2>

<p>An "API" (Application Programming Interface) is a set of protocols and tools for building software and applications. They have the advantage of simplifying complex code, so they can provide easier syntax to be used in its place (Mozilla, 2023). An API allows software to interact with other software. More specifically, a Web API, which is an application programming interface for the web, allows online interactions (W3Schools, 2023). An API serves as an entry point that enables programmers to program something in order to make something accessible for machines (Van Hooland & Verborgh, 2014). An API acts as a middle step in the process of data exchange between systems. This way, companies can co-operate with external developers, business partners, and other departments within their companies (IBM, 2023). APIs are used in many industry sectors, such as financial services, hospitality, healthcare, telecommunications, etc. (Oracle, 2023). APIs are beneficial for companies since they improve collaboration and communication, offer flexibility in their operations, offer layers of security between application, resulting to protection for the end-user as well (IBM, 2023).</p>

