<h2>Linked Data</h2>

<p>Linked Data is a set of guidelines for publishing interlinked, computer-readable data across the Web (Ontotext, 2023). The publishing of such data is done according to a set of best practices, the Linked Data Principles (Bizer, Vidal, Skaf-Molli, 2018). Linked data creates a dynamic perspective on data, allowing diverse data sources to connect in a standard way (Van Hooland & Verborgh, 2014). It utilizes foundational web tools like HTTP, RDF, and URIs. However, instead of just presenting web pages for human readers, it adapts them so that can be also read and interpreted by computers, aspiring that the internet can become a global database (Wikipedia, 2023), where more things can be discovered, enabling a web of data and not just a web of documents to be created (Berners-Lee, 2009). The term Linked Data is frequently used in pair with the term Semantic We. The two terms are closely connected, but not the same. For Semantic Web to properly work and provide solutions, a set of standards and technologies are required for computers to go beyond just reading data, but get to a point where data is understood well enough in order to build relationships between them. This is where linked data becomes relevant and essential (Yoose & Perkins, 2013).</p>

